# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chemical-bonding
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] A **chemical bond** is the association of atoms or ions to form molecules, crystals, and other structures.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The bond may result from the electrostatic force between oppositely charged ions, as in ionic bonds; the sharing of electrons, as in covalent bonds; or some combination of these effects.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Chemical bonds are described as having different strengths: there are "strong bonds" or "primary bonds" such as covalent, ionic and metallic bonds, and "weak bonds" or "secondary bonds" such as dipole–dipole interactions, the London dispersion force, and hydrogen bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Since opposite electric charges attract, the negatively charged electrons surrounding the nucleus and the positively charged protons within a nucleus attract each other.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Electrons shared between two nuclei will be attracted to both of them.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] "Constructive quantum mechanical wavefunction interference" stabilizes the paired nuclei (see Theories of chemical bonding).
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Bonded nuclei maintain an optimal distance (the bond distance) that balances attractive and repulsive effects, as explained quantitatively by quantum theory.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The atoms in molecules, crystals, metals and other forms of matter are held together by chemical bonds, which determine the structure and properties of matter.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] All bonds can be described by quantum theory, but, in practice, simplified rules and other theories allow chemists to predict the strength, directionality, and polarity of bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The octet rule and VSEPR theory are examples.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] More sophisticated theories are valence bond theory, which includes orbital hybridization and resonance, and molecular orbital theory, which includes the linear combination of atomic orbitals and ligand field theory.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Electrostatics is used to describe bond polarities and the effects they have on chemical substances.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] A chemical bond is an attraction between atoms.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] This attraction may be seen as the result of different behaviors of the outermost or valence electrons of atoms.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] These behaviors merge into each other seamlessly in various circumstances, so that there is no clear line to be drawn between them.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] However it remains useful and customary to differentiate between different types of bond, which result in different properties of condensed matter.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] In the simplest view of a covalent bond, one or more electrons (often a pair of electrons) are drawn into the space between the two atomic nuclei.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] This is not as a result of reduction in potential energy, because the attraction of the two electrons to the two protons is offset by the electron-electron and proton-proton repulsions.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Instead, the release of energy (and hence stability of the bond) arises from the reduction in kinetic energy due to the electrons being in a more spatially distributed (i.e. longer de Broglie wavelength) orbital compared with each electron being confined closer to its respective nucleus.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] These bonds exist between two particular identifiable atoms and have a direction in space, allowing them to be shown as single connecting lines between atoms in drawings, or modeled as sticks between spheres in models.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] In a polar covalent bond, one or more electrons are unequally shared between two nuclei.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Covalent bonds often result in the formation of small collections of better-connected atoms called molecules, which in solids and liquids are bound to other molecules by forces that are often much weaker than the covalent bonds that hold the molecules internally together.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Such weak intermolecular bonds give organic molecular substances, such as waxes and oils, their soft bulk character, and their low melting points (in liquids, molecules must cease most structured or oriented contact with each other).
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Also, the melting points of such covalent polymers and networks increase greatly.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] In a simplified view of an *ionic* bond, the bonding electron is not shared at all, but transferred.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] In this type of bond, the outer atomic orbital of one atom has a vacancy which allows the addition of one or more electrons.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] These newly added electrons potentially occupy a lower energy-state (effectively closer to more nuclear charge) than they experience in a different atom.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Thus, one nucleus offers a more tightly bound position to an electron than does another nucleus, with the result that one atom may transfer an electron to the other.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] This transfer causes one atom to assume a net positive charge, and the other to assume a net negative charge.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The *bond* then results from electrostatic attraction between the positive and negatively charged ions.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Ionic bonds may be seen as extreme examples of polarization in covalent bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Often, such bonds have no particular orientation in space, since they result from equal electrostatic attraction of each ion to all ions around them.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Ionic bonds are strong (and thus ionic substances require high temperatures to melt) but also brittle, since the forces between ions are short-range and do not easily bridge cracks and fractures.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] This type of bond gives rise to the physical characteristics of crystals of classic mineral salts, such as table salt.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] A less often mentioned type of bonding is *metallic* bonding.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] In this type of bonding, each atom in a metal donates one or more electrons to a "sea" of electrons that reside between many metal atoms.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] In this sea, each electron is free (by virtue of its wave nature) to be associated with a great many atoms at once.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The bond results because the metal atoms become somewhat positively charged due to loss of their electrons while the electrons remain attracted to many atoms, without being part of any given atom.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Metallic bonding may be seen as an extreme example of delocalization of electrons over a large system of covalent bonds, in which every atom participates.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] This type of bonding is often very strong (resulting in the tensile strength of metals).
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] However, metallic bonding is more collective in nature than other types, and so they allow metal crystals to more easily deform, because they are composed of atoms attracted to each other, but not in any particularly-oriented ways.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] This results in the malleability of metals.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The cloud of electrons in metallic bonding causes the characteristically good electrical and thermal conductivity of metals, and also their shiny lustre that reflects most frequencies of white light.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Working in the late 17th century, Robert Boyle developed the concept of a chemical element as substance different from a compound.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Near the end of the 18th century, a number of important developments in chemistry emerged without referring to the notion of an atomic theory.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The first was Antoine Lavoisier who showed that compounds consist of elements in constant proportion, redefining an element as a substance which scientists could not decompose into simpler substances by experimentation.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] This brought an end to the ancient idea of the elements of matter being fire, earth, air, and water, which had no experimental support.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Lavoisier showed that water can be decomposed into hydrogen and oxygen, which in turn he could not decompose into anything simpler, thereby proving these are elements.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Lavoisier also defined the law of conservation of mass, which states that in a chemical reaction, matter does not appear nor disappear into thin air; the total mass remains the same even if the substances involved were transformed.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] This definition distinguished compounds from mixtures.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] In the early years of the 19th century, Humphry Davy experimented on decomposing compounds into elements using the newly invention of the voltaic pile.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] This led to speculation that chemical bonding was related to electricity and in 1812 Jöns Jakob Berzelius published a theory of chemical combination stressing the electronegative and electropositive characters of the combining atoms.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] By the mid 19th century, Edward Frankland, F.A.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Couper, Alexander Butlerov, and Hermann Kolbe, building on the theory of radicals, developed the theory of valency, originally called "combining power", in which compounds were joined owing to an attraction of positive and negative poles.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] In 1904, Richard Abegg proposed his rule that the difference between the maximum and minimum valencies of an element is often eight.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The nature of the atom became clearer with Ernest Rutherford's 1911 discovery of an atomic nucleus surrounded by electrons.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] In his paper, Rutherford mentioned the model of Japanese physicist Hantaro Nagaoka, who had rejected Thomson's plum pudding model on the grounds that opposite charges are impenetrable.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] In 1904, Nagaoka had proposed an alternative planetary model of the atom in which a positively charged center is surrounded by a number of revolving electrons, in the manner of Saturn and its rings.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] At the 1911 Solvay Conference, in the discussion of what could regulate energy differences between atoms, Max Planck stated: "The intermediaries could be the electrons." These nuclear models suggested that electrons determine chemical behavior.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Next came Niels Bohr's 1913 model of a nuclear atom with electron orbits.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Also in 1916, Walther Kossel put forward a theory similar to Lewis' only his model assumed complete transfers of electrons between atoms, and was thus a model of ionic bonding.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Both Lewis and Kossel structured their bonding models on that of Abegg's rule (1904).
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Niels Bohr also proposed a model of the chemical bond in 1913.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] According to his model for a diatomic molecule, the electrons of the atoms of the molecule form a rotating ring whose plane is perpendicular to the axis of the molecule and equidistant from the atomic nuclei.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The dynamic equilibrium of the molecular system is achieved through the balance of forces between the forces of attraction of nuclei to the plane of the ring of electrons and the forces of mutual repulsion of the nuclei.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The Bohr model of the chemical bond took into account the Coulomb repulsion – the electrons in the ring are at the maximum distance from each other.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] In 1927, the first mathematically complete quantum description of a simple chemical bond, i.e. that produced by one electron in the hydrogen molecular ion, H2+, was derived by the Danish physicist Øyvind Burrau.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] This work showed that the quantum approach to chemical bonds could be fundamentally and quantitatively correct, but the mathematical methods used could not be extended to molecules containing more than one electron.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] A more practical, albeit less quantitative, approach was put forward in the same year by Walter Heitler and Fritz London.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The Heitler–London method forms the basis of what is now called valence bond theory.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] In 1929, the linear combination of atomic orbitals molecular orbital method (LCAO) approximation was introduced by Sir John Lennard-Jones, who also suggested methods to derive electronic structures of molecules of F2 (fluorine) and O2 (oxygen) molecules, from basic quantum principles.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] This molecular orbital theory represented a covalent bond as an orbital formed by combining the quantum mechanical Schrödinger atomic orbitals which had been hypothesized for electrons in single atoms.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The equations for bonding electrons in multi-electron atoms could not be solved to mathematical perfection (i.e., *analytically*), but approximations for them still gave many good qualitative predictions and results.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Most quantitative calculations in modern quantum chemistry use either valence bond or molecular orbital theory as a starting point, although a third approach, density functional theory, has become increasingly popular in recent years.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Coolidge carried out a calculation on the dihydrogen molecule that, unlike all previous calculation which used functions only of the distance of the electron from the atomic nucleus, used functions which also explicitly added the distance between the two electrons.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] With up to 13 adjustable parameters they obtained a result very close to the experimental result for the dissociation energy.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Later extensions have used up to 54 parameters and gave excellent agreement with experiments.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] This calculation convinced the scientific community that quantum theory could give agreement with experiment.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] However this approach has none of the physical pictures of the valence bond and molecular orbital theories and is difficult to extend to larger molecules.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Because atoms and molecules are three-dimensional, it is difficult to use a single method to indicate orbitals and bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] In **molecular formulas** the chemical bonds (binding orbitals) between atoms are indicated in different ways depending on the type of discussion.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] For example, in organic chemistry one is sometimes concerned only with the functional group of the molecule.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Sometimes, even the non-bonding valence shell electrons (with the two-dimensional approximate directions) are marked, e.g. for elemental carbon .'C'.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Some chemists may also mark the respective orbitals, e.g. the hypothetical ethene−4 anion (\/C=C/\ −4) indicating the possibility of bond formation.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Strong chemical bonds are the *intramolecular* forces that hold atoms together in molecules.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] A strong chemical bond is formed from the transfer or sharing of electrons between atomic centers and relies on the electrostatic attraction between the protons in nuclei and the electrons in the orbitals.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The types of strong bond differ due to the difference in electronegativity of the constituent elements.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Electronegativity is the tendency for an atom of a given chemical element to attract shared electrons when forming a chemical bond, where the higher the associated electronegativity then the more it attracts electrons.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Electronegativity serves as a simple way to quantitatively estimate the bond energy, which characterizes a bond along the continuous scale from covalent to ionic bonding.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] A large difference in electronegativity leads to more polar (ionic) character in the bond.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Ionic bonding is a type of electrostatic interaction between atoms that have a large electronegativity difference.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] There is no precise value that distinguishes ionic from covalent bonding, but an electronegativity difference of over 1.7 is likely to be ionic while a difference of less than 1.7 is likely to be covalent.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Ionic bonding leads to separate positive and negative ions.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Ionic charges are commonly between −3e to +3e.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Ionic bonding commonly occurs in metal salts such as sodium chloride (table salt).
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] A typical feature of ionic bonds is that the species form into ionic crystals, in which no ion is specifically paired with any single other ion in a specific directional bond.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Rather, each species of ion is surrounded by ions of the opposite charge, and the spacing between it and each of the oppositely charged ions near it is the same for all surrounding atoms of the same type.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] It is thus no longer possible to associate an ion with any specific other single ionized atom near it.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] This is a situation unlike that in covalent crystals, where covalent bonds between specific atoms are still discernible from the shorter distances between them, as measured via such techniques as X-ray diffraction.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Ionic crystals may contain a mixture of covalent and ionic species, as for example salts of complex acids such as sodium cyanide, NaCN.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] X-ray diffraction shows that in NaCN, for example, the bonds between sodium cations (Na+) and the cyanide anions (CN−) are *ionic*, with no sodium ion associated with any particular cyanide.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] However, the bonds between the carbon (C) and nitrogen (N) atoms in cyanide are of the *covalent* type, so that each carbon is strongly bound to *just one* nitrogen, to which it is physically much closer than it is to other carbons or nitrogens in a sodium cyanide crystal.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] When such crystals are melted into liquids, the ionic bonds are broken first because they are non-directional and allow the charged species to move freely.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Similarly, when such salts dissolve into water, the ionic bonds are typically broken by the interaction with water but the covalent bonds continue to hold.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] For example, in solution, the cyanide ions, still bound together as single CN− ions, move independently through the solution, as do sodium ions, as Na+.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] In water, charged ions move apart because each of them are more strongly attracted to a number of water molecules than to each other.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The attraction between ions and water molecules in such solutions is due to a type of weak dipole-dipole type chemical bond.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] In melted ionic compounds, the ions continue to be attracted to each other, but not in any ordered or crystalline way.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Covalent bonding is a common type of bonding in which two or more atoms share valence electrons more or less equally.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The simplest and most common type is a single bond in which two atoms share two electrons.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Other types include the double bond, the triple bond, one- and three-electron bonds, the three-center two-electron bond and three-center four-electron bond.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] In non-polar covalent bonds, the electronegativity difference between the bonded atoms is small, typically 0 to 0.3.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Bonds within most organic compounds are described as covalent.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The figure shows methane (CH4), in which each hydrogen forms a covalent bond with the carbon.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] See sigma bonds and pi bonds for LCAO descriptions of such bonding.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Molecules that are formed primarily from non-polar covalent bonds are often immiscible in water or other polar solvents, but much more soluble in non-polar solvents such as hexane.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] A polar covalent bond is a covalent bond with a significant ionic character.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] This means that the two shared electrons are closer to one of the atoms than the other, creating an imbalance of charge.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Such bonds occur between two atoms with moderately different electronegativities and give rise to dipole–dipole interactions.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The electronegativity difference between the two atoms in these bonds is 0.3 to 1.7.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] A single bond between two atoms corresponds to the sharing of one pair of electrons.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The Hydrogen (H) atom has one valence electron.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Two Hydrogen atoms can then form a molecule, held together by the shared pair of electrons.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Each H atom now has the noble gas electron configuration of helium (He).
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The pair of shared electrons forms a single covalent bond.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The electron density of these two bonding electrons in the region between the two atoms increases from the density of two non-interacting H atoms.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] A double bond has two shared pairs of electrons, one in a sigma bond and one in a pi bond with electron density concentrated on two opposite sides of the internuclear axis.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] A triple bond consists of three shared electron pairs, forming one sigma and two pi bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Quadruple and higher bonds are very rare and occur only between certain transition metal atoms.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] A coordinate covalent bond is a covalent bond in which the two shared bonding electrons are from the same one of the atoms involved in the bond.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] For example, boron trifluoride (BF3) and ammonia (NH3) form an adduct or coordination complex F3B←NH3 with a B–N bond in which a lone pair of electrons on N is shared with an empty atomic orbital on B.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] BF3 with an empty orbital is described as an electron pair acceptor or Lewis acid, while NH3 with a lone pair that can be shared is described as an electron-pair donor or Lewis base.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The electrons are shared roughly equally between the atoms in contrast to ionic bonding.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Such bonding is shown by an arrow pointing to the Lewis acid.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Transition metal complexes are generally bound by coordinate covalent bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] For example, the ion Ag+ reacts as a Lewis acid with two molecules of the Lewis base NH3 to form the complex ion Ag(NH3)2+, which has two Ag←N coordinate covalent bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] In metallic bonding, bonding electrons are delocalized over a lattice of atoms.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] By contrast, in ionic compounds, the locations of the binding electrons and their charges are static.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The free movement or delocalization of bonding electrons leads to classical metallic properties such as luster (surface light reflectivity), electrical and thermal conductivity, ductility, and high tensile strength.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] There are several types of weak bonds that can be formed between two or more molecules which are not covalently bound.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Intermolecular forces cause molecules to attract or repel each other.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Often, these forces influence physical characteristics (such as the melting point) of a substance.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Van der Waals forces are interactions between closed-shell molecules.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] They include both Coulombic interactions between partial charges in polar molecules, and Pauli repulsions between closed electrons shells.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Keesom forces are the forces between the permanent dipoles of two polar molecules.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] London dispersion forces are the forces between induced dipoles of different molecules.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] There can also be an interaction between a permanent dipole in one molecule and an induced dipole in another molecule.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Hydrogen bonds are responsible for the high boiling points of water and ammonia with respect to their heavier analogues.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] In some cases a similar halogen bond can be formed by a halogen atom located between two electronegative atoms on different molecules.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] At short distances, repulsive forces between atoms also become important.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] In the (unrealistic) limit of "pure" ionic bonding, electrons are perfectly localized on one of the two atoms in the bond.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Such bonds can be understood by classical physics.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The force between the atoms depends on isotropic continuum electrostatic potentials.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The magnitude of the force is in simple proportion to the product of the two ionic charges according to Coulomb's law.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Covalent bonds are better understood by valence bond (VB) theory or molecular orbital (MO) theory.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The properties of the atoms involved can be understood using concepts such as oxidation number, formal charge, and electronegativity.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The electron density within a bond is not assigned to individual atoms, but is instead delocalized between atoms.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] In valence bond theory, bonding is conceptualized as being built up from electron pairs that are localized and shared by two atoms via the overlap of atomic orbitals.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] The concepts of orbital hybridization and resonance augment this basic notion of the electron pair bond.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] In molecular orbital theory, bonding is viewed as being delocalized and apportioned in orbitals that extend throughout the molecule and are adapted to its symmetry properties, typically by considering linear combinations of atomic orbitals (LCAO).
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Valence bond theory is more chemically intuitive by being spatially localized, allowing attention to be focused on the parts of the molecule undergoing chemical change.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] In contrast, molecular orbitals are more "natural" from a quantum mechanical point of view, with orbital energies being physically significant and directly linked to experimental ionization energies from photoelectron spectroscopy.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Consequently, valence bond theory and molecular orbital theory are often viewed as competing but complementary frameworks that offer different insights into chemical systems.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] As approaches for electronic structure theory, both MO and VB methods can give approximations to any desired level of accuracy, at least in principle.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] However, at lower levels, the approximations differ, and one approach may be better suited for computations involving a particular system or property than the other.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Unlike the spherically symmetrical Coulombic forces in pure ionic bonds, covalent bonds are generally directed and anisotropic.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] These are often classified based on their symmetry with respect to a molecular plane as sigma bonds and pi bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] In the general case, atoms form bonds that are intermediate between ionic and covalent, depending on the relative electronegativity of the atoms involved.
[src:chemical-bonding/chemical-bond] Bonds of this type are known as polar covalent bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] A **covalent bond** is a chemical bond that involves the sharing of electrons to form electron pairs between atoms.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] These electron pairs are known as **shared pairs** or **bonding pairs**.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] The stable balance of attractive and repulsive forces between atoms, when they share electrons, is known as covalent bonding.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] For many molecules, the sharing of electrons allows each atom to attain the equivalent of a full valence shell, corresponding to a stable electronic configuration.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] In organic chemistry, covalent bonding is much more common than ionic bonding, where atoms are separate and merely associated by electrostatic attraction.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Covalent bonding also includes many kinds of interactions, including σ-bonding, π-bonding, metal-to-metal bonding, agostic interactions, bent bonds, three-center two-electron bonds and three-center four-electron bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] The term "covalence" was introduced by Irving Langmuir in 1919, with Nevil Sidgwick using "co-valent link" in the 1920s.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Merriam-Webster dates the specific phrase *covalent bond* to 1939, recognizing its first known use.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] The prefix *co-* (jointly, partnered) indicates that "co-valent" bonds involve shared "valence", as detailed in valence bond theory.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] In the molecule H 2, the hydrogen atoms share the two electrons via covalent bonding.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] The covalent character of a bond, as opposed to a more ionic nature, is greatest between atoms that have similar electronegativities, regardless of whether the elements are the same as each other.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Covalent bonding that entails the sharing of electrons over more than two atoms is said to be delocalized.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] The term *covalence* in regard to bonding was first used in 1919 by Irving Langmuir in a *Journal of the American Chemical Society* article entitled "The Arrangement of Electrons in Atoms and Molecules".
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] The idea of covalent bonding can be traced several years before 1919 to Gilbert N.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Lewis, who in 1916 described the sharing of electron pairs between atoms (and in 1926 he also coined the term "photon" for the smallest unit of radiant energy).
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] He introduced the *Lewis notation* or *electron dot notation* or *Lewis dot structure*, in which valence electrons (those in the outer shell) are represented as dots around the atomic symbols.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Pairs of electrons located between atoms represent covalent bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Multiple pairs represent multiple bonds, such as double bonds and triple bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] An alternative form of representation, not shown here, has bond-forming electron pairs represented as solid lines.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Lewis proposed that an atom forms enough covalent bonds to form a full (or closed) outer electron shell.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] In the diagram of methane shown here, the carbon atom has a valence of four and is, therefore, surrounded by eight electrons (the octet rule), four from the carbon itself and four from the hydrogens bonded to it.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Each hydrogen has a valence of one and is surrounded by two electrons (a duet rule) – its own one electron plus one from the carbon.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] The numbers of electrons correspond to full shells in the quantum theory of the atom; the outer shell of a carbon atom is the *n* = 2 shell, which can hold eight electrons, whereas the outer (and only) shell of a hydrogen atom is the *n* = 1 shell, which can hold only two.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] While the idea of shared electron pairs provides an effective qualitative picture of covalent bonding, quantum mechanics is needed to understand the nature of these bonds and predict the structures and properties of simple molecules.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Walter Heitler and Fritz London are credited with the first successful quantum mechanical explanation of a chemical bond (molecular hydrogen) in 1927.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Their work was based on the valence bond model, which assumes that a chemical bond is formed when there is good overlap between the atomic orbitals of participating atoms.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Atomic orbitals (except for s orbitals) have specific directional properties leading to different types of covalent bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Sigma (σ) bonds are the strongest covalent bonds and are due to head-on overlapping of orbitals on two different atoms.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Pi (π) bonds are weaker and are due to lateral overlap between p (or d) orbitals.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] A double bond between two given atoms consists of one σ and one π bond, and a triple bond is one σ and two π bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Covalent bonds are also affected by the electronegativity of the connected atoms which determines the chemical polarity of the bond.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Two atoms with equal electronegativity will make nonpolar covalent bonds such as H–H.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] An unequal relationship creates a polar covalent bond such as with H−Cl.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] However polarity also requires geometric asymmetry, or else dipoles may cancel out, resulting in a non-polar molecule.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] There are several types of structures for covalent substances, including individual molecules, molecular structures, macromolecular structures and giant covalent structures.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Individual molecules have strong bonds that hold the atoms together, but generally, there are negligible forces of attraction between molecules.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Such covalent substances are usually gases, for example, HCl, SO2, CO2, and CH4.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] In molecular structures, there are weak forces of attraction.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Such covalent substances are low-boiling-temperature liquids (such as ethanol), and low-melting-temperature solids (such as iodine and solid CO2).
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Macromolecular structures have large numbers of atoms linked by covalent bonds in chains, including synthetic polymers such as polyethylene and nylon, and biopolymers such as proteins and starch.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Network covalent structures (or giant covalent structures) contain large numbers of atoms linked in sheets (such as graphite), or 3-dimensional structures (such as diamond and quartz).
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] These substances have high melting and boiling points, are frequently brittle, and tend to have high electrical resistivity.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Elements that have high electronegativity, and the ability to form three or four electron pair bonds, often form such large macromolecular structures.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Bonds with one or three electrons can be found in radical species, which have an odd number of electrons.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] The simplest example of a 1-electron bond is found in the dihydrogen cation, H+ 2.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] One-electron bonds often have about half the bond energy of a 2-electron bond, and are therefore called "half bonds".
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] However, there are exceptions: in the case of dilithium, the bond is actually stronger for the 1-electron Li+ 2 than for the 2-electron Li2.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] This exception can be explained in terms of hybridization and inner-shell effects.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] The simplest example of three-electron bonding can be found in the helium dimer cation, He+ 2.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] It is considered a "half bond" because it consists of only one shared electron (rather than two); in molecular orbital terms, the third electron is in an anti-bonding orbital which cancels out half of the bond formed by the other two electrons.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Another example of a molecule containing a 3-electron bond, in addition to two 2-electron bonds, is nitric oxide, NO.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] The oxygen molecule, O2 can also be regarded as having two 3-electron bonds and one 2-electron bond, which accounts for its paramagnetism and its formal bond order of 2.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Chlorine dioxide and its heavier analogues bromine dioxide and iodine dioxide also contain three-electron bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Molecules with odd-electron bonds are usually highly reactive.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] These types of bond are only stable between atoms with similar electronegativities.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Dioxygen is sometimes represented as obeying the octet rule with a double bond (O=O) containing two pairs of shared electrons.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] However, the ground state of this molecule is paramagnetic, indicating the presence of unpaired electrons.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Pauling proposed that this molecule actually contains two three-electron bonds and one normal covalent (two-electron) bond.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] The octet on each atom then consists of two electrons from each three-electron bond, plus the two electrons of the covalent bond, plus one lone pair of non-bonding electrons.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] There are situations whereby a single Lewis structure is insufficient to explain the electron configuration in a molecule and its resulting experimentally-determined properties, hence a superposition of structures is needed.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] The same two atoms in such molecules can be bonded differently in different Lewis structures (a single bond in one, a double bond in another, or even none at all), resulting in a non-integer bond order.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] The nitrate ion is one such example with three equivalent structures.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] The bond between the nitrogen and each oxygen is a double bond in one structure and a single bond in the other two, so that the average bond order for each N–O interaction is ⁠2 + 1 + 1/3⁠ = ⁠4/3⁠.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] In organic chemistry, when a molecule with a planar ring obeys Hückel's rule, where the number of π electrons fit the formula 4*n* + 2 (where *n* is an integer), it attains extra stability and symmetry.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] In benzene, the prototypical aromatic compound, there are 6 π bonding electrons (*n* = 1, 4*n* + 2 = 6).
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] These occupy three delocalized π molecular orbitals (molecular orbital theory) or form conjugate π bonds in two resonance structures that linearly combine (valence bond theory), creating a regular hexagon exhibiting a greater stabilization than the hypothetical 1,3,5-cyclohexatriene.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] In the case of heterocyclic aromatics and substituted benzenes, the electronegativity differences between different parts of the ring may dominate the chemical behavior of aromatic ring bonds, which otherwise are equivalent.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Certain molecules such as xenon difluoride and sulfur hexafluoride have higher coordination numbers than would be possible due to strictly covalent bonding according to the octet rule.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] This is explained by the three-center four-electron bond ("3c–4e") model which interprets the molecular wavefunction in terms of non-bonding highest occupied molecular orbitals in molecular orbital theory and resonance of sigma bonds in valence bond theory.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] In three-center two-electron bonds ("3c–2e") three atoms share two electrons in bonding.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] This type of bonding occurs in boron hydrides such as diborane (B2H6), which are often described as electron deficient because there are not enough valence electrons to form localized (2-centre 2-electron) bonds joining all the atoms.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] However, the more modern description using 3c–2e bonds does provide enough bonding orbitals to connect all the atoms so that the molecules can instead be classified as electron-precise.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Each such bond (2 per molecule in diborane) contains a pair of electrons which connect the boron atoms to each other in a banana shape, with a proton (the nucleus of a hydrogen atom) in the middle of the bond, sharing electrons with both boron atoms.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] In certain cluster compounds, so-called four-center two-electron bonds also have been postulated.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] After the development of quantum mechanics, two basic theories were proposed to provide a quantum description of chemical bonding: valence bond (VB) theory and molecular orbital (MO) theory.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] A more recent quantum description is given in terms of atomic contributions to the electronic density of states.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] The two theories represent two ways to build up the electron configuration of the molecule.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] For valence bond theory, the atomic hybrid orbitals are filled with electrons first to produce a fully bonded valence configuration, followed by performing a linear combination of contributing structures (resonance) if there are several of them.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] In contrast, for molecular orbital theory, a linear combination of atomic orbitals is performed first, followed by filling of the resulting molecular orbitals with electrons.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] The two approaches are regarded as complementary, and each provides its own insights into the problem of chemical bonding.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] As valence bond theory builds the molecular wavefunction out of localized bonds, it is more suited for the calculation of bond energies and the understanding of reaction mechanisms.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] As molecular orbital theory builds the molecular wavefunction out of delocalized orbitals, it is more suited for the calculation of ionization energies and the understanding of spectral absorption bands.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] At the qualitative level, both theories contain incorrect predictions.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Simple (Heitler–London) valence bond theory correctly predicts the dissociation of homonuclear diatomic molecules into separate atoms, while simple (Hartree–Fock) molecular orbital theory incorrectly predicts dissociation into a mixture of atoms and ions.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] On the other hand, simple molecular orbital theory correctly predicts Hückel's rule of aromaticity, while simple valence bond theory incorrectly predicts that cyclobutadiene has larger resonance energy than benzene.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Although the wavefunctions generated by both theories at the qualitative level do not agree and do not match the stabilization energy by experiment, they can be corrected by configuration interaction.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] This is done by combining the valence bond covalent function with the functions describing all possible ionic structures or by combining the molecular orbital ground state function with the functions describing all possible excited states using unoccupied orbitals.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] It can then be seen that the simple molecular orbital approach overestimates the weight of the ionic structures while the simple valence bond approach neglects them.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] This can also be described as saying that the simple molecular orbital approach neglects electron correlation while the simple valence bond approach overestimates it.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Modern calculations in quantum chemistry usually start from (but ultimately go far beyond) a molecular orbital rather than a valence bond approach, not because of any intrinsic superiority in the former but rather because the MO approach is more readily adapted to numerical computations.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Molecular orbitals are orthogonal, which significantly increases the feasibility and speed of computer calculations compared to nonorthogonal valence bond orbitals.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Evaluation of bond covalency is dependent on the basis set for approximate quantum-chemical methods such as COOP (crystal orbital overlap population), COHP (Crystal orbital Hamilton population), and BCOOP (Balanced crystal orbital overlap population).
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] To overcome this issue, an alternative formulation of the bond covalency can be provided in this way.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] where the outer sum runs over all atoms A of the unit cell.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] The energy window ⁠ $[E_{0},E_{1}]$ ⁠ is chosen in such a way that it encompasses all of the relevant bands participating in the bond.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] If the range to select is unclear, it can be identified in practice by examining the molecular orbitals that describe the electron density along with the considered bond.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] where the contributions of the magnetic and spin quantum numbers are summed.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] In this formalism, the greater the value of ⁠ $C_{\mathrm {A,B} },$ ⁠ the higher the overlap of the selected atomic bands, and thus the electron density described by those orbitals gives a more covalent A−B bond.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] The quantity ⁠ $C_{\mathrm {A,B} }$ ⁠ is denoted as the *covalency* of the A−B bond, which is specified in the same units of the energy ⁠ E ⁠.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] An analogous effect to covalent binding is believed to occur in some nuclear systems, with the difference that the shared fermions are quarks rather than electrons.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] High energy proton-proton scattering cross-section indicates that quark interchange of either u or d quarks is the dominant process of the nuclear force at short distance.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] In particular, it dominates over the Yukawa interaction where a meson is exchanged.
[src:chemical-bonding/covalent-bond] Therefore, covalent binding by quark interchange is expected to be the dominating mechanism of nuclear binding at small distance when the bound hadrons have covalence quarks in common.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Unlike simple dipole–dipole interactions, hydrogen bonding arises from charge transfer (nB → σ*AH), orbital interactions, and quantum mechanical delocalization, making it a **resonance-assisted interaction** rather than a mere electrostatic attraction.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The general notation for hydrogen bonding is **Dn−H···Ac**, where the solid line represents a polar covalent bond, and the three dots indicate the hydrogen bond.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] **Hydrogen bond donors** have a protic hydrogen attached to an electronegative atom such as nitrogen (N), oxygen (O), and fluorine (F).
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] **Hydrogen bond acceptors** have a lone pair of electrons, such as the nitrogen atom of amines and amides and the oxygen atom of carboxylates and water.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The term "hydrogen bond" is generally used for well-defined, localized interactions with significant charge transfer and orbital overlap, such as those in DNA base pairing or ice.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] In contrast, "hydrogen-bonding interactions" is a broader term used when the interaction is weaker, more dynamic, or delocalized, such as in liquid water, supramolecular assemblies (e.g.: lipid membranes, protein-protein interactions), or weak C-H···O interactions.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] This distinction is particularly relevant in structural biology, materials science, and computational chemistry, where hydrogen bonding spans a continuum from weak van der Waals-like interactions to nearly covalent bonding.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Hydrogen bonding can occur between separate molecules (intermolecular) or within different parts of the same molecule (intramolecular).
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Its strength varies considerably, depending on geometry, environment, and the donor-acceptor pair, typically ranging from 4.2 to 167.4 kJ/mol (1 to 40 kcal/mol).
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] This places hydrogen bonds stronger than van der Waals interactions but generally weaker than covalent or ionic bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Hydrogen bonding plays a fundamental role in chemistry, biology, and materials science.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] It is responsible for the anomalously high boiling point of water, the stabilization of protein and nucleic acid structures, and key properties of materials like paper, wool, and hydrogels.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] In biological systems, hydrogen bonds mediate molecular recognition, enzyme catalysis, and DNA replication, while in materials science, they contribute to self-assembly, adhesion, and supramolecular organization.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] In a hydrogen bond, the electronegative atom not covalently attached to the hydrogen is named the proton acceptor, whereas the one covalently bound to the hydrogen is named the proton donor.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] This nomenclature is recommended by the IUPAC.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The hydrogen of the donor is protic and therefore can act as a Lewis acid and the acceptor is the Lewis base.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Hydrogen bonds are represented as H···Y system, where the dots represent the hydrogen bond.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Liquids that display hydrogen bonding (such as water) are called **associated liquids**.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Hydrogen bonds arise from a combination of electrostatics (multipole-multipole and multipole-induced multipole interactions), covalency (charge transfer by orbital overlap), and dispersion (London forces).
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] In weaker hydrogen bonds, hydrogen atoms tend to bond to elements such as sulfur (S) or chlorine (Cl); even carbon (C) can serve as a donor, particularly when the carbon or one of its neighbors is electronegative (e.g., in chloroform, aldehydes and terminal acetylenes).
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Gradually, it was recognized that there are many examples of weaker hydrogen bonding involving donor other than N, O, or F and/or acceptor Ac with electronegativity approaching that of hydrogen (rather than being much more electronegative).
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Although weak (about 4.2 kJ/mol (1 kcal/mol)), "non-traditional" hydrogen bonding interactions are ubiquitous and influence structures of many kinds of materials.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The definition of hydrogen bonding has gradually broadened over time to include these weaker attractive interactions.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] In 2011, an IUPAC Task Group recommended a modern evidence-based definition of hydrogen bonding, which was published in the IUPAC journal *Pure and Applied Chemistry*.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Hydrogen bonds can vary in strength from weak (1–2 kJ/mol) to strong (161.5 kJ/mol in the bifluoride ion, HF2-).
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The strength of intermolecular hydrogen bonds is most often evaluated by measurements of equilibria between molecules containing donor and/or acceptor units, most often in solution.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The strength of intramolecular hydrogen bonds can be studied with equilibria between conformers with and without hydrogen bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The most important method for the identification of hydrogen bonds also in complicated molecules is crystallography, sometimes also NMR-spectroscopy.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Structural details, in particular distances between donor and acceptor which are smaller than the sum of the van der Waals radii can be taken as indication of the hydrogen bond strength.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] One scheme gives the following somewhat arbitrary classification: those that are 63 to 167 kJ/mol (15 to 40 kcal/mol), 21 to 63 kJ/mol (5 to 15 kcal/mol), and 0 to 21 kJ/mol (0 to 5 kcal/mol) are considered strong, moderate, and weak, respectively.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Hydrogen bonds involving C−H bonds are both very rare and weak.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The **resonance assisted hydrogen bond** (commonly abbreviated as RAHB) is a strong type of hydrogen bond.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] It is characterized by the π-delocalization that involves the hydrogen atom and cannot be properly described by the electrostatic model alone.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] This description of the hydrogen bond has been proposed to describe unusually short distances generally observed between O=C−OH··· or ···O=C−C=C−OH.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The X−H distance is typically ≈110 pm, whereas the H···Y distance is ≈160 to 200 pm.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The typical length of a hydrogen bond in water is 197 pm.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The ideal bond angle depends on the nature of the hydrogen bond donor.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Strong hydrogen bonds are revealed by downfield shifts in the 1H NMR spectrum.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] For example, the acidic proton in the enol tautomer of acetylacetone appears at ⁠ $\delta _{\text{H}}$ ⁠ 15.5, which is about 10 ppm downfield of a conventional alcohol.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] In the IR spectrum, hydrogen bonding shifts the X−H stretching frequency to lower energy (i.e. the vibration frequency decreases).
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] This shift reflects a weakening of the X−H bond.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Certain hydrogen bonds - improper hydrogen bonds - show a blue shift of the X−H stretching frequency and a decrease in the bond length.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] H-bonds can also be measured by IR vibrational mode shifts of the acceptor.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The amide I mode of backbone carbonyls in α-helices shifts to lower frequencies when they form H-bonds with side-chain hydroxyl groups.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The dynamics of hydrogen bond structures in water can be probed by this OH stretching vibration.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The sudden weakening of hydrogen bonds during the solid-solid phase transition seems to be coupled with the onset of orientational or rotational disorder of the ions.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Hydrogen bonding is of persistent theoretical interest.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] According to a modern description O:H−O integrates both the intermolecular O:H lone pair ":" nonbond and the intramolecular H−O polar-covalent bond associated with O−O repulsive coupling.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Quantum chemical calculations of the relevant interresidue potential constants (compliance constants) revealed large differences between individual H bonds of the same type.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] For example, the central interresidue N−H···N hydrogen bond between guanine and cytosine is much stronger in comparison to the N−H···N bond between the adenine-thymine pair.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Theoretically, the bond strength of the hydrogen bonds can be assessed using NCI index, non-covalent interactions index, which allows a visualization of these non-covalent interactions, as its name indicates, using the electron density of the system.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Interpretations of the anisotropies in the Compton profile of ordinary ice claim that the hydrogen bond is partly covalent.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] However, this interpretation was challenged and subsequently clarified.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Most generally, the hydrogen bond can be viewed as a metric-dependent electrostatic scalar field between two or more intermolecular bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] This is slightly different from the intramolecular bound states of, for example, covalent or ionic bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] However, hydrogen bonding is generally still a bound state phenomenon, since the interaction energy has a net negative sum.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The initial theory of hydrogen bonding proposed by Linus Pauling suggested that the hydrogen bonds had a partial covalent nature.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] This interpretation remained controversial until NMR techniques demonstrated information transfer between hydrogen-bonded nuclei, a feat that would only be possible if the hydrogen bond contained some covalent character.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The concept of hydrogen bonding once was challenging.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Winmill with the first mention of the hydrogen bond, in 1912.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Moore and Winmill used the hydrogen bond to account for the fact that trimethylammonium hydroxide is a weaker base than tetramethylammonium hydroxide.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The description of hydrogen bonding in its better-known setting, water, came some years later, in 1920, from Latimer and Rodebush.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] In that paper, Latimer and Rodebush cited the work of a fellow scientist at their laboratory, Maurice Loyal Huggins, saying, "Mr.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] An ubiquitous example of a hydrogen bond is found between water molecules.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] In a discrete water molecule, there are two hydrogen atoms and one oxygen atom.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The simplest case is a pair of water molecules with one hydrogen bond between them, which is called the water dimer and is often used as a model system.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] When more molecules are present, as is the case with liquid water, more bonds are possible because the oxygen of one water molecule has two lone pairs of electrons, each of which can form a hydrogen bond with a hydrogen on another water molecule.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] This can repeat such that every water molecule is H-bonded with up to four other molecules, as shown in the figure (two through its two lone pairs, and two through its two hydrogen atoms).
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Hydrogen bonding strongly affects the crystal structure of ice, helping to create an open hexagonal lattice.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The density of ice is less than the density of water at the same temperature; thus, the solid phase of water floats on the liquid, unlike most other substances.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Liquid water's high boiling point is due to the high number of hydrogen bonds each molecule can form, relative to its low molecular mass.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Owing to the difficulty of breaking these bonds, water has a very high boiling point, melting point, and viscosity compared to otherwise similar liquids not conjoined by hydrogen bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Water is unique because its oxygen atom has two lone pairs and two hydrogen atoms, meaning that the total number of bonds of a water molecule is up to four.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The number of hydrogen bonds formed by a molecule of liquid water fluctuates with time and temperature.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] From TIP4P liquid water simulations at 25 °C, it was estimated that each water molecule participates in an average of 3.59 hydrogen bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] At 100 °C, this number decreases to 3.24 due to the increased molecular motion and decreased density, while at 0 °C, the average number of hydrogen bonds increases to 3.69.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Another study found a much smaller number of hydrogen bonds: 2.357 at 25 °C.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Defining and counting the hydrogen bonds is not straightforward however.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Because water may form hydrogen bonds with solute proton donors and acceptors, it may competitively inhibit the formation of solute intermolecular or intramolecular hydrogen bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Consequently, hydrogen bonds between or within solute molecules dissolved in water are almost always unfavorable relative to hydrogen bonds between water and the donors and acceptors for hydrogen bonds on those solutes.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Hydrogen bonds between water molecules have an average lifetime of 10−11 seconds, or 10 picoseconds.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] A single hydrogen atom can participate in two hydrogen bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] This type of bonding is called "bifurcated" (split in two or "two-forked").
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] It can exist, for instance, in complex organic molecules.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] It has been suggested that a bifurcated hydrogen atom is an essential step in water reorientation.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Acceptor-type hydrogen bonds (terminating on an oxygen's lone pairs) are more likely to form bifurcation (it is called overcoordinated oxygen, OCO) than are donor-type hydrogen bonds, beginning on the same oxygen atom's hydrogen atoms.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] For example, hydrogen fluoride—which has three lone pairs on the F atom but only one H atom—can form only two bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Ammonia has the opposite problem: three hydrogen atoms but only one lone pair.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Hydrogen bonding plays an important role in determining the three-dimensional structures and the properties adopted by many proteins.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Compared to the C−C, C−O, and C−N bonds that comprise most polymers, hydrogen bonds are far weaker, perhaps 5% as strong.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Thus, hydrogen bonds can be broken by chemical or mechanical means while retaining the basic structure of the polymer backbone.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] This hierarchy of bond strengths (covalent bonds being stronger than hydrogen-bonds being stronger than van der Waals forces) is relevant in the properties of many materials.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] In these macromolecules, bonding between parts of the same macromolecule cause it to fold into a specific shape, which helps determine the molecule's physiological or biochemical role.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] For example, the double helical structure of DNA is due largely to hydrogen bonding between its base pairs (as well as pi stacking interactions), which link one complementary strand to the other and enable replication.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] In the secondary structure of proteins, hydrogen bonds form between the backbone oxygens and amide hydrogens.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] When the spacing of the amino acid residues participating in a hydrogen bond occurs regularly between positions *i* and *i* + 4, an alpha helix is formed.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] When the spacing is less, between positions *i* and *i* + 3, then a 310 helix is formed.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] When two strands are joined by hydrogen bonds involving alternating residues on each participating strand, a beta sheet is formed.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Hydrogen bonds also play a part in forming the tertiary structure of protein through interaction of R-groups.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Bifurcated H-bond systems are common in alpha-helical transmembrane proteins between the backbone amide C=O of residue *i* as the H-bond acceptor and two H-bond donors from residue *i* + 4: the backbone amide N−H and a side-chain hydroxyl or thiol H+.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The energy preference of the bifurcated H-bond hydroxyl or thiol system is −14 or 167 kJ/mol (−3.4 or 40 kcal/mol) respectively.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] This type of bifurcated H-bond provides an intrahelical H-bonding partner for polar side-chains, such as serine, threonine, and cysteine within the hydrophobic membrane environments.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The role of hydrogen bonds in protein folding has also been linked to osmolyte-induced protein stabilization.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Protective osmolytes, such as trehalose and sorbitol, shift the protein folding equilibrium toward the folded state, in a concentration dependent manner.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] While the prevalent explanation for osmolyte action relies on excluded volume effects that are entropic in nature, circular dichroism (CD) experiments have shown osmolyte to act through an enthalpic effect.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The molecular mechanism for their role in protein stabilization is still not well established, though several mechanisms have been proposed.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Computer molecular dynamics simulations suggest that osmolytes stabilize proteins by modifying the hydrogen bonds in the protein hydration layer.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Several studies have shown that hydrogen bonds play an important role for the stability between subunits in multimeric proteins.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] For example, a study of sorbitol dehydrogenase displayed an important hydrogen bonding network which stabilizes the tetrameric quaternary structure within the mammalian sorbitol dehydrogenase protein family.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] A protein backbone hydrogen bond incompletely shielded from water attack is a dehydron.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Dehydrons promote the removal of water through proteins or ligand binding.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The exogenous dehydration enhances the electrostatic interaction between the amide and carbonyl groups by de-shielding their partial charges.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Furthermore, the dehydration stabilizes the hydrogen bond by destabilizing the nonbonded state consisting of dehydrated isolated charges.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Wool, being a protein fibre, is held together by hydrogen bonds, causing wool to recoil when stretched.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] However, washing at high temperatures can permanently break the hydrogen bonds and a garment may permanently lose its shape.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The properties of many polymers are affected by hydrogen bonds within and/or between the chains.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Prominent examples include cellulose and its derived fibers, such as cotton and flax.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] In nylon, hydrogen bonds between carbonyl and the amide N*H* effectively link adjacent chains, which gives the material mechanical strength.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Hydrogen bonds also affect the aramid fibre, where hydrogen bonds stabilize the linear chains laterally.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The chain axes are aligned along the fibre axis, making the fibres extremely stiff and strong.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Hydrogen-bond networks make both polymers sensitive to humidity levels in the atmosphere because water molecules can diffuse into the surface and disrupt the network.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Some polymers are more sensitive than others.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Thus nylons are more sensitive than aramids, and nylon 6 more sensitive than nylon-11.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] A symmetric hydrogen bond is a special type of hydrogen bond in which the proton is spaced exactly halfway between two identical atoms.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The strength of the bond to each of those atoms is equal.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] It is an example of a three-center four-electron bond.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] This type of bond is much stronger than a "normal" hydrogen bond.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The effective bond order is 0.5, so its strength is comparable to a covalent bond.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] It is seen in ice at high pressure, and also in the solid phase of many anhydrous acids such as hydrofluoric acid and formic acid at high pressure.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] It is also seen in the bifluoride ion [F···H···F]−.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Due to severe steric constraint, the protonated form of Proton Sponge (1,8-bis(dimethylamino)naphthalene) and its derivatives also have symmetric hydrogen bonds ([N···H···N]+), although in the case of protonated Proton Sponge, the assembly is bent.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The hydrogen bond can be compared with the closely related dihydrogen bond, which is also an intermolecular bonding interaction involving hydrogen atoms.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] These structures have been known for some time, and well characterized by crystallography; however, an understanding of their relationship to the conventional hydrogen bond, ionic bond, and covalent bond remains unclear.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Generally, the hydrogen bond is characterized by a proton acceptor that is a lone pair of electrons in nonmetallic atoms (most notably in the nitrogen, and chalcogen groups).
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] In some cases, these proton acceptors may be pi-bonds or metal complexes.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] In the dihydrogen bond, however, a metal hydride serves as a proton acceptor, thus forming a hydrogen-hydrogen interaction.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Neutron diffraction has shown that the molecular geometry of these complexes is similar to hydrogen bonds, in that the bond length is very adaptable to the metal complex/hydrogen donor system.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] The hydrogen bond is relevant to drug design.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] According to Lipinski's rule of five the majority of orally active drugs have no more than five hydrogen bond donors and fewer than ten hydrogen bond acceptors.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] These interactions exist between nitrogen–hydrogen and oxygen–hydrogen centers.
[src:chemical-bonding/hydrogen-bond] Many drugs do not, however, obey these "rules".
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] Ionic compounds conduct electricity when molten or in solution, typically not when solid.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] Ionic compounds generally have a high melting point, depending on the charge of the ions they consist of.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] The higher the charges the stronger the cohesive forces and the higher the melting point.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] They also tend to be soluble in water; the stronger the cohesive forces, the lower the solubility.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] Atoms that have an almost full or almost empty valence shell tend to be very reactive.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] Strongly electronegative atoms (such as halogens) often have only one or two empty electron states in their valence shell, and frequently bond with other atoms or gain electrons to form anions.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] Weakly electronegative atoms (such as alkali metals) have relatively few valence electrons, which can easily be lost to strongly electronegative atoms.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] As a result, weakly electronegative atoms tend to distort their electron cloud and form cations.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] Ionic bonding can result from a redox reaction when atoms of an element (usually metal), whose ionization energy is low, give some of their electrons to achieve a stable electron configuration.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] An atom of another element (usually nonmetal) with greater electron affinity accepts one or more electrons to attain a stable electron configuration, and after accepting electrons an atom becomes an anion.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] Typically, the stable electron configuration is one of the noble gases for elements in the s-block and the p-block, and particular stable electron configurations for d-block and f-block elements.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] The electrostatic attraction between the anions and cations leads to the formation of a solid with a crystallographic lattice in which the ions are stacked in an alternating fashion.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] In such a lattice, it is usually not possible to distinguish discrete molecular units, so that the compounds formed are not molecular.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] However, the ions themselves can be complex and form molecular ions like the acetate anion or the ammonium cation.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] For example, common table salt is sodium chloride.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] When sodium (Na) and chlorine (Cl) are combined, the sodium atoms each lose an electron, forming cations (Na+), and the chlorine atoms each gain an electron to form anions (Cl−).
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] These ions are then attracted to each other in a 1:1 ratio to form sodium chloride (NaCl).
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] However, to maintain charge neutrality, strict ratios between anions and cations are observed so that ionic compounds, in general, obey the rules of stoichiometry despite not being molecular compounds.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] For compounds that are transitional to the alloys and possess mixed ionic and metallic bonding, this may not be the case anymore.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] Many sulfides, e.g., do form non-stoichiometric compounds.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] The salt NaCl is then said to consist of the acid rest Cl− and the base rest Na+.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] The removal of electrons to form the cation is endothermic, raising the system's overall energy.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] There may also be energy changes associated with breaking of existing bonds or the addition of more than one electron to form anions.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] However, the action of the anion's accepting the cation's valence electrons and the subsequent attraction of the ions to each other releases (lattice) energy and, thus, lowers the overall energy of the system.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] Ionic bonding will occur only if the overall energy change for the reaction is favorable.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] In general, the reaction is exothermic, but, e.g., the formation of mercuric oxide (HgO) is endothermic.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] The charge of the resulting ions is a major factor in the strength of ionic bonding, e.g. a salt C+A− is held together by electrostatic forces roughly four times weaker than C2+A2− according to Coulomb's law, where C and A represent a generic cation and anion respectively.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] The sizes of the ions and the particular packing of the lattice are ignored in this rather simplistic argument.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] Ionic compounds in the solid state form lattice structures.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] The two principal factors in determining the form of the lattice are the relative charges of the ions and their relative sizes.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] Some structures are adopted by a number of compounds; for example, the structure of the rock salt sodium chloride is also adopted by many alkali halides, and binary oxides such as magnesium oxide.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] For a solid crystalline ionic compound the enthalpy change in forming the solid from gaseous ions is termed the lattice energy.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] The experimental value for the lattice energy can be determined using the Born–Haber cycle.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] It can also be calculated (predicted) using the Born–Landé equation as the sum of the electrostatic potential energy, calculated by summing interactions between cations and anions, and a short-range repulsive potential energy term.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] The electrostatic potential can be expressed in terms of the interionic separation and a constant (Madelung constant) that takes account of the geometry of the crystal.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] The further away from the nucleus the weaker the shield.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] The Born–Landé equation gives a reasonable fit to the lattice energy of, e.g., sodium chloride, where the calculated (predicted) value is −756 kJ/mol, which compares to −787 kJ/mol using the Born–Haber cycle.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] In aqueous solution the binding strength can be described by the Bjerrum or Fuoss equation as function of the ion charges, rather independent of the nature of the ions such as polarizability or size.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] The strength of salt bridges is most often evaluated by measurements of equilibria between molecules containing cationic and anionic sites, most often in solution.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] Equilibrium constants in water indicate additive free energy contributions for each salt bridge.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] Another method for the identification of hydrogen bonds in complicated molecules is crystallography, sometimes also NMR-spectroscopy.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] The attractive forces defining the strength of ionic bonding can be modeled by Coulomb's law.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] Ionic bond strengths are typically (cited ranges vary) between 170 and 1500 kJ/mol.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] Ions in crystal lattices of purely ionic compounds are spherical; however, if the positive ion is small and/or highly charged, it will distort the electron cloud of the negative ion, an effect summarized in Fajans' rules.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] This polarization of the negative ion leads to a build-up of extra charge density between the two nuclei, that is, to partial covalency.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] Larger negative ions are more easily polarized, but the effect is usually important only when positive ions with charges of 3+ (e.g., Al3+) are involved.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] However, 2+ ions (Be2+) or even 1+ (Li+) show some polarizing power because their sizes are so small (e.g., LiI is ionic but has some covalent bonding present).
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] Note that this is not the ionic polarization effect that refers to the displacement of ions in the lattice due to the application of an electric field.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] In ionic bonding, the atoms are bound by the attraction of oppositely charged ions, whereas, in covalent bonding, atoms are bound by sharing electrons to attain stable electron configurations.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] In covalent bonding, the molecular geometry around each atom is determined by valence shell electron pair repulsion VSEPR rules, whereas, in ionic materials, the geometry follows maximum packing rules.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] One could say that covalent bonding is more *directional* in the sense that the energy penalty for not adhering to the optimum bond angles is large, whereas ionic bonding has no such penalty.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] There are no shared electron pairs to repel each other, the ions should simply be packed as efficiently as possible.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] This often leads to much higher coordination numbers.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] In NaCl, each ion has 6 bonds and all bond angles are 90°.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] By comparison, carbon typically has a maximum of four bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] Purely ionic bonding cannot exist, as the proximity of the entities involved in the bonding allows some degree of sharing electron density between them.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] Therefore, all ionic bonding has some covalent character.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] Thus, bonding is considered ionic where the ionic character is greater than the covalent character.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] The larger the difference in electronegativity between the two types of atoms involved in the bonding, the more ionic (polar) it is.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] Bonds with partially ionic and partially covalent character are called polar covalent bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] For example, Na–Cl and Mg–O interactions have a few percent covalency, while Si–O bonds are usually ~50% ionic and ~50% covalent.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] Pauling estimated that an electronegativity difference of 1.7 (on the Pauling scale) corresponds to 50% ionic character, so that a difference greater than 1.7 corresponds to a bond which is predominantly ionic.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] Ionic character in covalent bonds can be directly measured for atoms having quadrupolar nuclei (2H, 14N, 81,79Br, 35,37Cl or 127I).
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] These nuclei are generally objects of NQR nuclear quadrupole resonance and NMR nuclear magnetic resonance studies.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] where the *eq*zz term corresponds to the principal component of the EFG tensor and *e* is the elementary charge.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] In turn, the electric field gradient opens the way to description of bonding modes in molecules when the QCC values are accurately determined by NMR or NQR methods.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] In general, when ionic bonding occurs in the solid (or liquid) state, it is not possible to talk about a single "ionic bond" between two individual atoms, because the cohesive forces that keep the lattice together are of a more collective nature.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] This is quite different in the case of covalent bonding, where we can often speak of a distinct bond localized between two particular atoms.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] However, even if ionic bonding is combined with some covalency, the result is *not* necessarily discrete bonds of a localized character.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] In such cases, the resulting bonding often requires description in terms of a band structure consisting of gigantic molecular orbitals spanning the entire crystal.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] Thus, the bonding in the solid often retains its collective rather than localized nature.
[src:chemical-bonding/ionic-bonding] When the difference in electronegativity is decreased, the bonding may then lead to a semiconductor, a semimetal or eventually a metallic conductor with metallic bonding.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Metallic bonding is not the only type of chemical bonding a metal can exhibit as a pure substance.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] For example, elemental gallium consists of covalently-bound pairs of atoms in both liquid and solid-state—these pairs form a crystal structure with metallic bonding between them.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Another example of a metal–metal covalent bond is the mercurous ion (Hg2+ 2).
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] As chemistry developed into a science, it became clear that metals formed the majority of the periodic table of the elements, and great progress was made in the description of the salts that can be formed in reactions with acids.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] With the advent of electrochemistry, it became clear that metals generally go into solution as positively charged ions, and the oxidation reactions of the metals became well understood in their electrochemical series.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] A picture emerged of metals as positive ions held together by an ocean of negative electrons.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] With the advent of quantum mechanics, this picture was given a more formal interpretation in the form of the free electron model and its further extension, the nearly free electron model.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] In both models, the electrons are seen as a gas traveling through the structure of the solid with an energy that is essentially isotropic, in that it depends on the square of the magnitude, *not* the direction of the momentum vector **k**.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] In three-dimensional k-space, the set of points of the highest filled levels (the Fermi surface) should therefore be a sphere.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] In the nearly-free model, box-like Brillouin zones are added to k-space by the periodic potential experienced from the (ionic) structure, thus mildly breaking the isotropy.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The advent of X-ray diffraction and thermal analysis made it possible to study the structure of crystalline solids, including metals and their alloys; and phase diagrams were developed.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Despite all this progress, the nature of intermetallic compounds and alloys largely remained a mystery, and their study was often merely empirical.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Chemists generally steered away from anything that did not seem to follow Dalton's laws of multiple proportions; and the problem was considered the domain of a different science, metallurgy.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The nearly-free electron model was eagerly taken up by some researchers in metallurgy, notably Hume-Rothery, in an attempt to explain why intermetallic alloys with certain compositions would form and others would not.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Initially, Hume-Rothery's attempts were quite successful.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] His idea was to add electrons to inflate the spherical Fermi-balloon inside the series of Brillouin-boxes and determine when a certain box would be full.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] This predicted a fairly large number of alloy compositions that were later observed.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] As soon as cyclotron resonance became available and the shape of the balloon could be determined, it was found that the balloon was not spherical as the Hume-Rothery believed, except perhaps in the case of caesium.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] This revealed how a model can sometimes give a whole series of correct predictions, yet still be wrong in its basic assumptions.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The nearly-free electron debacle compelled researchers to modify the assumpition that ions flowed in a sea of free electrons.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] A number of quantum mechanical models were developed, such as band structure calculations based on molecular orbitals, and the density functional theory.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] These models either depart from the atomic orbitals of neutral atoms that share their electrons, or (in the case of density functional theory) departs from the total electron density.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The free-electron picture has, nevertheless, remained a dominant one in introductory courses on metallurgy.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The electronic band structure model became a major focus for the study of metals and even more of semiconductors.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Together with the electronic states, the vibrational states were also shown to form bands.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Rudolf Peierls showed that, in the case of a one-dimensional row of metallic atoms, an inevitable instability would break such a chain into individual molecules.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] This sparked an interest as to when collective metallic bonding is stable, and when localized bonding will take its place.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Further research went into the study of clustering of metal atoms.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] As powerful as the band structure model proved to be in describing metallic bonding, it remains a one-electron approximation of a many-body problem: the energy states of an individual electron are described as if all the other electrons form a homogeneous background.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] This gave a better explanation for the transition from localized unpaired electrons to itinerant ones partaking in metallic bonding.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The combination of two phenomena gives rise to metallic bonding: delocalization of electrons and the availability of a far larger number of delocalized energy states than of delocalized electrons.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The latter could be called electron deficiency.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Graphene is an example of two-dimensional metallic bonding.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Its metallic bonds are similar to aromatic bonding in benzene, naphthalene, anthracene, ovalene, etc.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Metal aromaticity in metal clusters is another example of delocalization, this time often in three-dimensional arrangements.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Metals take the delocalization principle to its extreme, and one could say that a crystal of a metal represents a single molecule over which all conduction electrons are delocalized in all three dimensions.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] This means that inside the metal, one can generally not distinguish molecules, so that the metallic bonding is neither intra- nor inter-molecular.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Metallic bonding is mostly non-polar, because there is little to no difference, even in alloys, among the electronegativities of the atoms participating in the bonding interaction.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Thus, metallic bonding is an extremely delocalized communal form of covalent bonding.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Metallic bonding may be described as not a unique type of bond at all, as it describes the bonding only as present in a portion of condensed matter, be it crystalline solid or liquid.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Metallic vapors, in contrast, are often atomic (Hg) or at times contain molecules, such as Na2, held together by a more conventional covalent bond.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] This is why it is not correct to speak of a single 'metallic bond'.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Delocalization is most pronounced for **s**- and **p**-electrons.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Delocalization in caesium is so strong that the electrons are virtually freed from the caesium atoms to form a gas constrained only by the surface of the metal.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] For caesium, therefore, the picture of Cs+ ions held together by a negatively charged electron gas is very close to accurate (though not perfectly so).
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] For other elements the electrons are less free, in that they still experience the potential of the metal atoms, sometimes quite strongly.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] They require a more intricate quantum mechanical treatment (e.g., tight binding) in which the atoms are viewed as neutral, much like the carbon atoms in benzene.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] For **d**- and especially **f**-electrons the delocalization is not strong at all and this explains why these electrons are able to continue behaving as unpaired electrons that retain their spin, adding interesting magnetic properties to these metals.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Metal atoms contain few electrons in their valence shells relative to their periods or energy levels.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] They are electron-deficient elements and the communal sharing does not change that.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] There remain far more available energy states than there are shared electrons.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Both requirements for conductivity are therefore fulfilled: strong delocalization and partly filled energy bands.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Such electrons can therefore easily change from one energy state to a slightly different one.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Thus, not only do they become delocalized, forming a sea of electrons permeating the structure, but they are also able to migrate through the structure when an external electrical field is applied, leading to electrical conductivity.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Without the field, there are electrons moving equally in all directions.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Within such a field, some electrons will adjust their state slightly, adopting a different wave vector.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Consequently, there will be more moving one way than another and a net current will result.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Metals are typically also good conductors of heat.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Thermal conductivity in metals is primarily due to free electrons, and is generally tied to the electrical conductivity of the same substance, due to the Wiedemann–Franz law.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Many factors can also influence thermal conductivity, such as temperature.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The freedom of electrons to migrate also gives metal atoms, or layers of them, the capacity to slide past each other.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Locally, bonds can easily be broken and replaced by new ones after a deformation.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] This process does not affect the communal metallic bonding very much, which gives rise to metals' characteristic malleability and ductility.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] This is particularly true for pure elements.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] In the presence of dissolved impurities, the normally easily formed cleavages may be blocked and the material becomes harder.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Gold, for example, is very soft in pure form (24-karat), which is why alloys are preferred in jewelry.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Electron deficiency is important in distinguishing metallic from more conventional covalent bonding.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Thus, to amend the expression given above: *Metallic bonding is an extremely delocalized communal form of electron-deficient covalent bonding*.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The metallic radius is defined as one-half of the distance between the two adjacent metal ions in the metallic structure.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] This radius depends on the nature of the atom as well as its environment—specifically, on the coordination number (CN), which in turn depends on the temperature and applied pressure.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] When comparing periodic trends in the size of atoms it is often desirable to apply the so-called Goldschmidt correction, which converts atomic radii to the values the atoms would have if they were 12-coordinated.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Since metallic radii are largest for the highest coordination number, correction for less dense coordinations involves multiplying by x, where 0 < x < 1.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The correction is named after Victor Goldschmidt who obtained the numerical values quoted above.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The radii follow general periodic trends: they decrease across the period due to the increase in the effective nuclear charge, which is not offset by the increased number of valence electrons; but the radii increase down the group due to an increase in the principal quantum number.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Between the 4**d** and 5**d** elements, the lanthanide contraction is observed—there is very little increase of the radius down the group due to the presence of poorly shielding **f** orbitals.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The atoms in metals are held together by electrostatic attractions between the positively charged cations and the delocalized negatively charged electron cloud around them.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The attraction between the cations and electron cloud is strong, and the attraction gets stronger the more valence electrons the metal atoms provide for the electron cloud.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] For example, magnesium has a higher melting and boiling point than sodium because magnesium has two valence electrons compared to sodium's one valence electron.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] A magnesium atom provides two electrons for the electron cloud (twice the amount a sodium atom can) and becomes a +2 ion.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The denser electron cloud and more positively charged ions result in a much stronger attractive force between them, which increases the melting point of magnesium.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Besides other types of chemical bonding, boiling is the only way a pure metal can have no metallic bonding; molten metals are still affected by metallic bonding.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] This takes a lot of energy, due to the strength of the attractive forces holding the delocalized electron cloud and the cations together.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Therefore, metals often have high boiling points, with the transition metal tungsten having the highest melting and boiling points among all elements.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] An exception is the elements of the zinc group: Zn, Cd, and Hg.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Their electron configurations end in ...n**s**2, which resembles a noble gas configuration, like that of helium.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The melting and boiling points decrease more and more when going down the zinc group, because the energy differential to the empty n**p** orbitals becomes larger.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] These metals are therefore relatively volatile, and are avoided in ultra-high vacuum systems.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The energy of a metallic bond is thus mostly a function of the number of electrons which surround the metallic atom, as exemplified by the embedded atom model.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] This typically results in metals assuming relatively simple, close-packed crystal structures, such as FCC, BCC, and HCP.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Given high enough cooling rates and appropriate alloy composition, metallic bonding can occur even in glasses, which have amorphous structures.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Many things in biochemistry are mediated by the weak interaction of metal ions and biomolecules.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Such interactions, and their associated conformational changes, have been measured using dual polarisation interferometry.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Pure metals are insoluble in water or organic solvents, unless they undergo a reaction with them.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Typically, this is an oxidation reaction that robs the metal atoms of their valence electrons, destroying the metallic bonding.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] However, metals are often readily soluble in each other while retaining the metallic character of their bonding.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Gold, for example, dissolves easily in mercury, even at room temperature.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Even in solid metals, the solubility can be extensive.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] If the structures of the two metals are the same, there can even be complete solid solubility, as in the case of electrum, an alloy of silver and gold.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] At times, however, two metals will form alloys with different structures than either of the two parents, such as in intermetallic compounds.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] But, because materials with metallic bonding are typically not molecular, Dalton's law of integral proportions is not valid; and often a range of stoichiometric ratios can be achieved.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] It is thus better to describe phases instead of solutes or pure substances.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The study of such phases has traditionally been more the domain of metallurgy than of chemistry, although the two fields overlap considerably.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The metallic bonding in complex compounds does not necessarily involve all constituent elements equally.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] It is quite possible to have one or more elements that do not partake at all.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] One could picture the conduction electrons flowing around them like a river around an island or a big rock.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] It is possible to observe which elements do partake: e.g., by looking at the core levels in an X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) spectrum.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] If an element partakes, its peaks tend to be skewed.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Some intermetallic materials do exhibit metal clusters reminiscent of molecules; these compounds are more a topic of chemistry than of metallurgy.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The formation of the clusters could be seen as a way to localize the electron-deficient bonding into bonds of a more condensed nature.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Hydrogen is an extreme example of this form of condensation, where at high pressures it is metallic.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The core of the planet Jupiter is held together by a combination of metallic bonding and high pressure induced by gravity.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] At lower pressures, however, the bonding becomes entirely localized into a regular covalent bond.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The localization is so complete that H2 gas results.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] A similar argument holds for an element such as boron.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Though it is electron-deficient compared to carbon, it does not form a metal.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Instead it has a number of complex structures in which icosahedral B12 clusters dominate.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Charge density waves are a related phenomenon.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] As these phenomena involve the movement of the atoms toward or away from each other, they can be interpreted as the coupling between the electronic and the vibrational states (i.e. the phonons) of the material.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] A different such electron-phonon interaction is thought to lead to a very different result at low temperatures, that of superconductivity.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Rather than blocking the mobility of the charge carriers by forming electron pairs in localized bonds, Cooper pairs are formed that no longer experience any resistance to their mobility.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The presence of an ocean of mobile charge carriers has profound effects on the optical properties of metals, which can only be understood by considering the electrons as a *collective*, rather than considering the states of individual electrons involved in more conventional covalent bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Light consists of a combination of an electrical and a magnetic field.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The electrical field is usually able to excite an elastic response from the electrons involved in the metallic bonding.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The result is that photons cannot penetrate very far into the metal and are typically reflected, although some may also be absorbed.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] This holds equally for all photons in the visible spectrum, which is why metals are often silvery white or grayish with the characteristic specular reflection of metallic lustre.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The balance between reflection and absorption determines how white or how gray a metal is, although surface tarnish can obscure the lustre.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Silver, a metal with high conductivity, is one of the whitest.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Notable exceptions are reddish copper and yellowish gold.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The reason for their color is that there is an upper limit to the frequency of the light that metallic electrons can readily respond to, which is the plasmon frequency.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] At the plasmon frequency, the frequency-dependent dielectric function of the free electron gas goes from negative (reflecting) to positive (transmitting); higher frequency photons are not reflected at the surface, and do not contribute to the color of the metal.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] There are some materials, such as indium tin oxide (ITO), that are metallic conductors (actually degenerate semiconductors) for which this threshold is in the infrared, which is why they are transparent in the visible, but good reflectors in the infrared.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] For silver the limiting frequency is in the far ultraviolet, but for copper and gold it is closer to the visible.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] This explains the colors of these two metals.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] At the surface of a metal, resonance effects known as surface plasmons can result.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] They are collective oscillations of the conduction electrons, like a ripple in the electronic ocean.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] However, even if photons have enough energy, they usually do not have enough momentum to set the ripple in motion.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Therefore, plasmons are hard to excite on a bulk metal.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] This is why gold and copper look like lustrous metals albeit with a dash of color.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] However, in colloidal gold the metallic bonding is confined to a tiny metallic particle, which prevents the oscillation wave of the plasmon from 'running away'.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] The momentum selection rule is therefore broken, and the plasmon resonance causes an extremely intense absorption in the green, with a resulting purple-red color.
[src:chemical-bonding/metallic-bonding] Such colors are orders of magnitude more intense than ordinary absorptions seen in dyes and the like, which involve individual electrons and their energy states.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] In chemistry, **valence bond (VB) theory** is one of the two basic theories, along with molecular orbital (MO) theory, that were developed to use the methods of quantum mechanics to describe chemical bonding.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] It focuses on how the atomic orbitals of the dissociated atoms combine to give individual chemical bonds when a molecule is formed.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] In contrast, molecular orbital theory has orbitals that cover the whole molecule.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Lewis proposed that a chemical bond forms by the interaction of two shared bonding electrons, with the representation of molecules as Lewis structures.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] In 1916, Walther Kossel put forth his theory of the ionic chemical bond (octet rule), also independently advanced in the same year by Gilbert N.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Kossel put forward a theory similar to that of Lewis theory, except that Kossel supposed complete transfers of electrons between atoms, a model of ionic bonding.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Both Lewis and Kossel based their bonding models on Abegg's rule (1904) that the difference between the maximum positive and negative valences of an element is frequently eight.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] In 1921 the chemist Charles Rugeley Bury suggested that eight and eighteen electrons in a shell form stable configurations.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Bury proposed that the electron configurations in transitional elements depended upon the valence electrons in their outer shell.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Although there is no mathematical formula either in chemistry or quantum mechanics for the arrangement of electrons in the atom, the hydrogen atom can be described by the Schrödinger equation and the Matrix Mechanics equation both derived in 1925.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] However, for hydrogen alone, in 1927 the Heitler–London theory was formulated which for the first time enabled the calculation of bonding properties of the hydrogen molecule H2 based on quantum mechanical considerations.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Specifically, Walter Heitler determined how to use Schrödinger's wave equation (1926) to show how two hydrogen atom wavefunctions join together, with plus, minus, and exchange terms, to form a covalent bond.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] He then called up his associate Fritz London and they worked out the details of the theory over the course of the night.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Later, Linus Pauling used the pair bonding ideas of Lewis together with Heitler–London theory to develop two other key concepts in VB theory: resonance (1928) and orbital hybridization (1930).
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] According to Charles Coulson, author of the noted 1952 book *Valence*, this period marks the start of "modern valence bond theory", as contrasted with older valence bond theories, which are essentially electronic theories of valence couched in pre-wave-mechanical terms.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Linus Pauling published in 1931 his landmark paper on valence bond theory: "On the Nature of the Chemical Bond".
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Building on this article, Pauling's 1939 textbook: *On the Nature of the Chemical Bond* would become what some have called the bible of modern chemistry.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] This book helped experimental chemists to understand the impact of quantum theory on chemistry.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] However, the later edition in 1959 failed to adequately address the problems that appeared to be better understood by molecular orbital theory.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] The impact of valence theory declined during the 1960s and 1970s as molecular orbital theory grew in usefulness as it was implemented in large digital computer programs.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Since the 1980s, the more difficult problems, of implementing valence bond theory into computer programs, have been solved largely, and valence bond theory has seen a resurgence.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] According to this theory a **covalent** **bond** is formed between two atoms by the overlap of *half filled valence* atomic orbitals of each atom containing one unpaired electron.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Valence Bond theory describes chemical bonding better than Lewis Theory, which states that atoms share or transfer electrons so that they achieve the octet rule.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] It does not take into account orbital interactions or bond angles, and treats all covalent bonds equally.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] A valence bond structure resembles a Lewis structure, but when a molecule cannot be fully represented by a single Lewis structure, multiple valence bond structures are used.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Each of these VB structures represents a specific Lewis structure.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] This combination of valence bond structures is the main point of resonance theory.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Valence bond theory considers that the overlapping atomic orbitals of the participating atoms form a chemical bond.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Because of the overlapping, it is most probable that electrons should be in the bond region.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Valence bond theory views bonds as weakly coupled orbitals (small overlap).
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Valence bond theory is typically easier to employ in ground state molecules.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] The core orbitals and electrons remain essentially unchanged during the formation of bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] The overlapping atomic orbitals can differ.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] The two types of overlapping orbitals are sigma and pi.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Sigma bonds occur when the orbitals of two shared electrons overlap head-to-head, with the electron density most concentrated between nuclei.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Pi bonds occur when two orbitals overlap when they are parallel.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] For example, a bond between two *s*-orbital electrons is a sigma bond, because two spheres are always coaxial.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] In terms of bond order, single bonds have one sigma bond, double bonds consist of one sigma bond and one pi bond, and triple bonds contain one sigma bond and two pi bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] However, the atomic orbitals for bonding may be hybrids.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Hybridization is a model that describes how atomic orbitals combine to form new orbitals that better match the geometry of molecules.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Atomic orbitals that are similar in energy combine to make hybrid orbitals.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] For example, the carbon in methane (CH4) undergoes sp3 hybridization to form four equivalent orbitals, resulting in a tetrahedral shape.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Different types of hybridization, such as sp, sp2, and sp3, correspond to specific molecular geometries (linear, trigonal planar, and tetrahedral), influencing the bond angles observed in molecules.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Hybrid orbitals provide additional directionality to sigma bonds, accurately explaining molecular geometries.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Valence bond theory complements molecular orbital theory (MO), which does not adhere to the valence bond idea that electron pairs are localized between two specific atoms in a molecule, but that they are distributed in sets of molecular orbitals which can extend over the entire molecule.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Although both theories describe chemical bonding, MO generally offer a clearer and more reliable framework for predicting magnetic and ionization properties (and therefore optical and IR spectra).
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] In particular, molecular orbitals can effectively account for paramagnetism arising from unpaired electrons, whereas VBT struggles.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Simple VB theory includes only covalent structures (for neutral molecules), but can be refined by adding terms for ionic structures to the wave function.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Similarly simple MO theory considers a single electron configuration, with no correlation between the movement of different electrons, but correlation can be included by adding other configurations.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] If many terms are considered in the wave functions, the two theories approach mathematical equivalence, However MO is a more popular approach than VB due to its easier implementation in the early days of computational chemistry.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Valence bond theory views aromatic properties of molecules as due to spin coupling of the π orbitals.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] This is essentially still the old idea of resonance between Friedrich August Kekulé von Stradonitz and James Dewar structures.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] In contrast, molecular orbital theory views aromaticity as delocalization of the π-electrons.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Valence bond treatments are restricted to relatively small molecules, largely due to the lack of orthogonality between valence bond orbitals and between valence bond structures.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] The molecular orbitals are always orthogonal.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Valence bond theory cannot explain electronic transitions and spectroscopic properties as effectively as MO theory.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] While VB employs hybridization to explain bonding, it can oversimplify complex bonding situations, limiting its applicability in more intricate molecular geometries such as transition metal compounds.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] On the other hand, VB theory provides a much more intuitive picture of the reorganization of electronic charge that takes place when bonds are broken and formed during the course of a chemical reaction.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Valence bond theory also correctly predicts the dissociation of homonuclear diatomic molecules into separate atoms even in the simplest models, while similarly crude MO approaches predict dissociation into a mixture of atoms and ions.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] For example, the MO function for dihydrogen is an equal mixture of the covalent and ionic valence bond structures and so predicts incorrectly that the molecule would dissociate into an equal mixture of hydrogen atoms and hydrogen positive and negative ions.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Modern valence bond theory replaces the overlapping atomic orbitals by overlapping valence bond orbitals that are expanded over a large number of basis functions, either centered each on one atom to give a classical valence bond picture, or centered on all atoms in the molecule.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] The resulting energies are more competitive with energies from calculations where electron correlation is introduced based on a Hartree–Fock reference wavefunction.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] The most recent text is by Shaik and Hiberty.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] An important aspect of the valence bond theory is the condition of maximum overlap, which leads to the formation of the strongest possible bonds.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] This theory is used to explain the covalent bond formation in many molecules.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] For example, in the case of the F2 molecule, the F−F bond is formed by the overlap of *p**z* orbitals of the two F atoms, each containing an unpaired electron.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Since the nature of the overlapping orbitals are different in H2 and F2 molecules, the bond strength and bond lengths differ between H2 and F2 molecules.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] In methane (CH4), the carbon atom undergoes sp3 hybridization, allowing it to form four equivalent sigma bonds with hydrogen atoms, resulting in a tetrahedral geometry.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Hybridization also explains the equal C-H bond strengths.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] In an HF molecule the covalent bond is formed by the overlap of the 1*s* orbital of H and the 2*p**z* orbital of F, each containing an unpaired electron.
[src:chemical-bonding/valence-bond-theory] Mutual sharing of electrons between H and F results in a covalent bond in HF.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] In molecular physics and chemistry, the **van der Waals force** (sometimes **van der Waals' force**) is a distance-dependent interaction between atoms or molecules.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] Unlike ionic or covalent bonds, these attractions do not result from a chemical electronic bond; they are comparatively weak and therefore more susceptible to disturbance.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] The van der Waals force quickly vanishes at longer distances between interacting molecules.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] Named after Dutch physicist Johannes Diderik van der Waals, the Van der Waals force plays a fundamental role in fields as diverse as supramolecular chemistry, structural biology, polymer science, nanotechnology, surface science, and condensed matter physics.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] It also underlies many properties of organic compounds and molecular solids, including their solubility in polar and non-polar media.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] If no other force is present, the distance between atoms at which the force becomes repulsive rather than attractive as the atoms approach one another is called the **van der Waals contact distance**; this phenomenon results from the mutual repulsion between the atoms' electron clouds.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] Van der Waals forces include attraction and repulsions between atoms, molecules, as well as other intermolecular forces.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] They differ from covalent and ionic bonding in that they are caused by correlations in the fluctuating polarizations of nearby particles (a consequence of quantum dynamics).
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] The force results from a transient shift in electron density.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] Specifically, the electron density may temporarily shift to be greater on one side of the nucleus.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] This shift generates a transient charge which a nearby atom can be attracted to or repelled by.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] The force is repulsive at very short distances, reaches zero at an equilibrium distance characteristic for each atom, or molecule, and becomes attractive for distances larger than the equilibrium distance.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] For individual atoms, the equilibrium distance is between 0.3 nm and 0.5 nm, depending on the atomic-specific diameter.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] When the interatomic distance is greater than 1.0 nm the force is not strong enough to be easily observed as it decreases as a function of distance *r* approximately with the 7th power (~*r*−7).
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] Van der Waals forces are often among the weakest chemical forces.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] For example, the pairwise attractive van der Waals interaction energy between H (hydrogen) atoms in different H2 molecules equals 0.06 kJ/mol (0.6 meV) and the pairwise attractive interaction energy between O (oxygen) atoms in different O2 molecules equals 0.44 kJ/mol (4.6 meV).
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] The strength of van der Waals bonds increases with higher polarizability of the participating atoms.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] For example, the pairwise Van der Waals interaction energy for more polarizable atoms such as S (sulfur) atoms in H2S and sulfides exceeds 1 kJ/mol (10 meV), and the pairwise interaction energy between even larger, more polarizable Xe (xenon) atoms is 2.35 kJ/mol (24.3 meV).
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] These van der Waals interactions are up to 40 times stronger than in H2, which has only one valence electron, and they are still not strong enough to achieve an aggregate state other than gas for Xe (noble gas) under standard conditions.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] The interactions between atoms in metals can also be effectively described as van der Waals interactions and account for the observed solid aggregate state with bonding strengths comparable to covalent and ionic interactions.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] Accordingly, van der Waals forces can range from weak to strong interactions, and support integral structural loads when multitudes of such interactions are present.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] More broadly, intermolecular forces have several possible contributions.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] Attractive or repulsive electrostatic interactions between permanent charges (in the case of molecular ions), dipoles (in the case of molecules without inversion centre), quadrupoles (all molecules with symmetry lower than cubic), and in general between permanent multipoles.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] These interactions also include hydrogen bonds, cation-pi, and pi-stacking interactions.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] Orientation-averaged contributions from electrostatic interactions are sometimes called the Keesom interaction or Keesom force after Willem Hendrik Keesom.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] Induction (also known as polarization), which is the attractive interaction between a permanent multipole on one molecule with an induced multipole on another.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] This interaction is sometimes called Debye force after Peter J.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] The interactions (2) and (3) are labelled polar Interactions.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] Dispersion (usually named London dispersion interactions after Fritz London), which is the attractive interaction between any pair of molecules, including non-polar atoms, arising from the interactions of instantaneous multipoles.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] When to apply the term "van der Waals" force depends on the text.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] The broadest definitions include all intermolecular forces which are electrostatic in origin, namely (2), (3) and (4).
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] Some authors, whether or not they consider other forces to be of van der Waals type, focus on (3) and (4) as these are the components which act over the longest range.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] All intermolecular/Van der Waals forces are anisotropic (except those between two noble gas atoms), which means that they depend on the relative orientation of the molecules.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] The induction and dispersion interactions are always attractive, irrespective of orientation, but the electrostatic interaction changes sign upon rotation of the molecules.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] That is, the electrostatic force can be attractive or repulsive, depending on the mutual orientation of the molecules.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] When molecules are in thermal motion, as they are in the gas and liquid phase, the electrostatic force is averaged out to a large extent because the molecules thermally rotate and thus probe both repulsive and attractive parts of the electrostatic force.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] Random thermal motion can disrupt or overcome the electrostatic component of the van der Waals force but the averaging effect is much less pronounced for the attractive induction and dispersion forces.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] The Lennard-Jones potential is often used as an approximate model for the isotropic part of a total (repulsion plus attraction) van der Waals force as a function of distance.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] Van der Waals forces are responsible for certain cases of pressure broadening (van der Waals broadening) of spectral lines and the formation of van der Waals molecules.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] The London–van der Waals forces are related to the Casimir effect for dielectric media, the former being the microscopic description of the latter bulk property.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] The first detailed calculations of this were done in 1955 by E.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] A more general theory of van der Waals forces has also been developed.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] In low molecular weight alcohols, the hydrogen-bonding properties of their polar hydroxyl group dominate other weaker van der Waals interactions.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] In higher molecular weight alcohols, the properties of the nonpolar hydrocarbon chain(s) dominate and determine their solubility.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] Van der Waals forces are also responsible for the weak hydrogen bond interactions between unpolarized dipoles particularly in acid-base aqueous solution and between biological molecules.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] London dispersion forces, named after the German-American physicist Fritz London, are weak intermolecular forces that arise from the interactive forces between instantaneous multipoles in molecules without permanent multipole moments.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] In and between organic molecules the multitude of contacts can lead to larger contribution of dispersive attraction, particularly in the presence of heteroatoms.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] London dispersion forces are also known as 'dispersion forces', 'London forces', or 'instantaneous dipole–induced dipole forces'.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] The strength of London dispersion forces is proportional to the polarizability of the molecule, which in turn depends on the total number of electrons and the area over which they are spread.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] Hydrocarbons display small dispersive contributions, the presence of heteroatoms lead to increased LDFs as function of their polarizability, e.g. in the sequence RI>RBr>RCl>RF.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] In absence of solvents weakly polarizable hydrocarbons form crystals due to dispersive forces; their sublimation heat is a measure of the dispersive interaction.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] For macroscopic bodies with known volumes and numbers of atoms or molecules per unit volume, the total van der Waals force is often computed based on the "microscopic theory" as the sum over all interacting pairs.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] It is necessary to integrate over the total volume of the object, which makes the calculation dependent on the objects' shapes.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] The Van der Waals *force* between two spheres of constant radii (*R*1 and *R*2 are treated as parameters) is then a function of separation since the force on an object is the negative of the derivative of the potential energy function, $\ F_{\rm {VdW}}(z)=-{\frac {d}{dz}}U(z)$ .
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] The van der Waals forces between objects with other geometries using the Hamaker model have been published in the literature.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] From the expression above, it is seen that the van der Waals force decreases with decreasing size of bodies (R).
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] Nevertheless, the strength of inertial forces, such as gravity and drag/lift, decrease to a greater extent.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] Consequently, the van der Waals forces become dominant for collections of very small particles such as very fine-grained dry powders (where there are no capillary forces present) even though the force of attraction is smaller in magnitude than it is for larger particles of the same substance.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] Such powders are said to be cohesive, meaning they are not as easily fluidized or pneumatically conveyed as their more coarse-grained counterparts.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] Generally, free-flow occurs with particles greater than about 250 μm.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] The Van der Waals force of adhesion is also dependent on the surface topography.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] If there are surface asperities, or protuberances, that result in a greater total area of contact between two particles or between a particle and a wall, this increases the van der Waals force of attraction as well as the tendency for mechanical interlocking.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] The microscopic theory assumes pairwise additivity.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] It neglects many-body interactions and retardation.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] A more rigorous approach accounting for these effects, called the "macroscopic theory", was developed by Lifshitz in 1956.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] Langbein derived a much more cumbersome "exact" expression in 1970 for spherical bodies within the framework of the Lifshitz theory while a simpler macroscopic model approximation had been made by Derjaguin as early as 1934.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] Expressions for the Van der Waals forces for many different geometries using the Lifshitz theory have likewise been published.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] There were efforts in 2008 to create a dry glue that exploits the effect, and success was achieved in 2011 to create an adhesive tape on similar grounds (i.e. based on van der Waals forces).
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] In 2011, a paper was published relating the effect to both velcro-like hairs and the presence of lipids in gecko footprints.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] A later study suggested that capillary adhesion might play a role, but that hypothesis has been rejected by more recent studies.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] A 2014 study has shown that gecko adhesion to smooth Teflon and polydimethylsiloxane surfaces is mainly determined by electrostatic interaction (caused by contact electrification), not van der Waals or capillary forces.
[src:chemical-bonding/van-der-waals-force] Among the arthropods, some spiders have similar setae on their scopulae or scopula pads, enabling them to climb or hang upside-down from extremely smooth surfaces such as glass or porcelain.
